## Summary

When a session is driven by a CLI/ACP backend (e.g. Claude Code CLI), OpenClaw's own transcript only records the inbound user messages. `/export-session` would still produce a "successful" HTML export with empty summary stats and no assistant/tool/usage data, which is misleading.

This change detects the backend-delegated case (a transcript whose message entries are exclusively `role: user`) and surfaces a clear warning in:
- the command reply text, and
- the exported HTML header (via a new `warning` field in the session data payload).

Closes #90844 (minimum-fix option 2).

## Changes

- `src/auto-reply/reply/commands-export-session.ts`
  - Adds `isBackendDelegatedSession()` guard.
  - Embeds `warning` into `SessionData` and the command reply text when the guard fires.
- `src/auto-reply/reply/export-html/template.js`
  - Renders the warning as a visible banner above the session header.
- `src/auto-reply/reply/export-html/template.css`
  - Styles the warning banner with the existing warning color.
- `src/auto-reply/reply/commands-export-session.test.ts`
  - Adds regression tests for the warning (user-only transcript) and the non-warning case (mixed transcript).

## Verification

- `pnpm test src/auto-reply/reply/commands-export-session.test.ts --run` — 9/9 pass.
- `pnpm build` — completed successfully (export HTML templates copied, CLI/bootstrap checks pass).
- `pnpm exec oxfmt --check` on changed TS/JS/CSS files — clean.
- `pnpm dlx oxlint@latest -c .oxlintrc.json` on changed TS files — clean.

## Real behavior proof

**Behavior addressed:** `/export-session` produces a misleading successful export for backend-delegated sessions whose transcript contains only `role: user` messages, with no warning that assistant/tool/usage data are missing.

**Real environment tested:** Local Linux checkout of this branch, Node v22.22.0, pnpm 11.2.2.

**Exact steps or command run after this patch:**

Save the standalone proof script below as `repro-90867-proof.mjs` in the repo root and run it:

```bash
cd /home/0668000780/开源社区提交2/openclaw
node --import tsx repro-90867-proof.mjs
```

<details>
<summary>Standalone proof script (<code>repro-90867-proof.mjs</code>)</summary>

```js
#!/usr/bin/env node
// Real-behavior proof for PR #90867.
// Creates an OpenClaw session transcript that contains only user messages
// (the signature of a backend-delegated / CLI / ACP session) and runs the
// actual production export handler against it on the local filesystem.
import fs from "node:fs/promises";
import os from "node:os";
import path from "node:path";
import { buildExportSessionReply } from "./src/auto-reply/reply/commands-export-session.js";

const sessionId = "backend-delegated-demo";
const sessionKey = "agent:default:backend-delegated-demo";
const agentId = "default";

async function main() {
  const tmpDir = await fs.mkdtemp(path.join(os.tmpdir(), "repro-90867-"));
  const sessionsDir = path.join(tmpDir, "agents", agentId, "sessions");
  const storePath = path.join(sessionsDir, "sessions.json");
  const transcriptPath = path.join(sessionsDir, `${sessionId}.jsonl`);

  await fs.mkdir(sessionsDir, { recursive: true });

  // 1. Create a sessions.json store entry pointing at the transcript.
  const store = {
    [sessionKey]: {
      sessionId,
      updatedAt: Date.now(),
      sessionFile: transcriptPath,
    },
  };
  await fs.writeFile(storePath, JSON.stringify(store, null, 2));

  // 2. Write a backend-delegated transcript: only role:user messages.
  const entries = [
    {
      type: "message",
      id: "msg-1",
      parentId: null,
      timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
      message: { role: "user", content: "Hello from a backend-delegated session" },
    },
    {
      type: "message",
      id: "msg-2",
      parentId: "msg-1",
      timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
      message: { role: "user", content: "Only user messages are recorded here" },
    },
  ];
  await fs.writeFile(transcriptPath, entries.map((e) => JSON.stringify(e)).join("\n"));

  // 3. Invoke the real production export handler.
  const params = {
    cfg: {},
    ctx: {},
    command: {
      commandBodyNormalized: "/export-session",
      isAuthorizedSender: true,
      senderIsOwner: true,
      senderId: "sender-1",
      channel: "quietchat",
      surface: "quietchat",
      ownerList: [],
      rawBodyNormalized: "/export-session",
    },
    sessionEntry: store[sessionKey],
    sessionKey,
    workspaceDir: tmpDir,
    directives: {},
    elevated: { enabled: true, allowed: true, failures: [] },
    defaultGroupActivation: () => "mention",
    resolvedVerboseLevel: "off",
    resolvedReasoningLevel: "off",
    resolveDefaultThinkingLevel: async () => undefined,
    provider: "openai",
    model: "gpt-5.4",
    contextTokens: 0,
    isGroup: false,
    storePath,
  };

  const reply = await buildExportSessionReply(params);

  // 4. Read the exported HTML and confirm the warning is present in the
  //    base64 session-data payload and that the warning CSS rule is bundled.
  const htmlFiles = (await fs.readdir(tmpDir)).filter((f) => f.endsWith(".html"));
  if (htmlFiles.length !== 1) {
    throw new Error(`Expected one exported HTML file, got ${htmlFiles.length}`);
  }
  const htmlPath = path.join(tmpDir, htmlFiles[0]);
  const html = await fs.readFile(htmlPath, "utf-8");

  const warningText = "This session was handled by a backend runtime";
  const replyHasWarning = typeof reply.text === "string" && reply.text.includes(warningText);

  const sessionDataMatch = html.match(/<script\s+id="session-data"[^>]*>([A-Za-z0-9+/=]*)<\/script>/);
  if (!sessionDataMatch) {
    throw new Error("Could not locate base64 session data in exported HTML");
  }
  const decoded = Buffer.from(sessionDataMatch[1], "base64").toString("utf-8");
  const sessionData = JSON.parse(decoded);
  const htmlHasWarning = typeof sessionData.warning === "string" && sessionData.warning.includes(warningText);
  const cssHasWarning = html.includes(".export-warning");

  console.log("=== Reproduction #90867 ===");
  console.log("Command reply text:");
  console.log(reply.text);
  console.log("");
  console.log(`Exported HTML: ${htmlPath}`);
  console.log(`Reply contains warning: ${replyHasWarning}`);
  console.log(`HTML session data contains warning: ${htmlHasWarning}`);
  console.log(`HTML CSS includes .export-warning rule: ${cssHasWarning}`);

  if (!replyHasWarning || !htmlHasWarning || !cssHasWarning) {
    throw new Error("Backend-delegated warning was not emitted");
  }

  console.log("PASS: backend-delegated warning shown in command reply and exported HTML payload");
}

main().catch((err) => {
  console.error(err);
  process.exit(1);
});
```
</details>

**Evidence after fix:**

```
=== Reproduction #90867 ===
Command reply text:
✅ Session exported!

📄 File: openclaw-session-backend--2026-06-16T12-22-53.html
📊 Entries: 2
⚠️ This session was handled by a backend runtime (e.g. CLI/ACP). Assistant replies, tool calls, and usage data are stored in the backend transcript and are not included in this export.
🧠 System prompt: 17,249 chars
🔧 Tools: 35

Exported HTML: /tmp/repro-90867-kdygqI/openclaw-session-backend--2026-06-16T12-22-53.html
Reply contains warning: true
HTML session data contains warning: true
HTML CSS includes .export-warning rule: true
PASS: backend-delegated warning shown in command reply and exported HTML payload
```

**Observed result after fix:** When the transcript contains only `role: user` messages, the production `/export-session` handler emits the backend-delegated warning in the command reply and embeds the same warning into the exported HTML's session-data payload, where the bundled template renders it as a visible banner via the new `.export-warning` CSS rule.

**What was not tested:** Live click-through of the exported HTML in a browser; the warning banner rendering was verified by inspecting the decoded session-data payload and the bundled CSS rule. A full managed-service Dashboard or Claude Code CLI integration test was not run because the proof exercises the same production handler and transcript format those backends use.

## Summary

Fixes #93891

When `plugins.entries.openai` already exists alongside the legacy `openai-codex` entry, `rewritePluginEntries` would silently delete the legacy entry without merging its config — losing fields like `baseUrl`, `reasoningEffort`, etc.

## Root Cause

The original code only handled the single-key case (legacy-only). When both keys existed, it skipped the assignment branch and fired `delete` unconditionally, dropping all legacy fields.

## Change

`src/commands/doctor/shared/legacy-config-migrations.runtime.providers.ts` — +31 lines

Added `deepMergePluginEntry` helper that recursively merges legacy keys into the canonical entry, with canonical winning on true conflicts. This mirrors the behavior that `migrateLegacyOpenAICodexProvider` already implements for the model-level equivalent.

### Before
```ts
// input: {openai:{config:{embeddingModel:"text-embedding-3-large"}}, "openai-codex":{config:{baseUrl:"https://chatgpt.com/backend-api/codex", reasoningEffort:"high"}}}
// after rewritePluginEntries:
// ❌ {openai:{config:{embeddingModel:"text-embedding-3-large"}}} — baseUrl + reasoningEffort gone
```

### After
```ts
// ✅ {openai:{config:{embeddingModel:"text-embedding-3-large", baseUrl:"https://chatgpt.com/backend-api/codex", reasoningEffort:"high"}}}
```

